\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 83. L. album} (Coincy) Sennen, {\i op. cit.} 72 (1936). Like{\b  81} but plant 30-50 cm; leaves whitish; lamina c. 15 × 20 mm, 5-veined; petiole c. 30 mm, canaliculate; spikes up to 1·8 cm, with 4 spikelets per cm; spikelets 1- to 2-flowered; inner bract c. 3 mm, truncate; calyx 3·2-3·8 mm; corolla c. 4·5 mm. 2n = 18. {\i Gypsaceous soils. • S.E. Spain }({\i near Lorca}). Hs.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 84. L. cymuliferum} (Boiss.) Sauvage & Vindt,{\i  Fl. Maroc}{\b  1:} 68 (1952) ({\i Statice gummifera }Durieu ex Boiss. & Reuter). Plant 20-40 cm, glabrous, smooth. Leaves 30-50 × 14-22 mm, spathulate, whitish; lamina suborbicular, emarginate, often mucronate; petiole 20-40 × 2-4 mm, widening below into a reddish sheath and often with conspicuous resin glands. Inflorescence without non-flowering branches; scales 6-12 mm. Spikes up to 1 cm; spikelets 1- to 6-flowered. Inner bract c. 2·5 mm. Calyx 2·8-3·2 mm. Corolla c. 4 mm, white. 2n = 16. {\i Maritime cliffs and salt-marshes, and saline soils inland. S. Spain.} Hs. ({\i N. Africa}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Variants with 1-flowered (var. {\i uniflorum} Pignatti), 2- to 3-flowered (var.{\i  cymuliferum}) and 4- to 6-flowered (var. {\i corymbulosum} Cosson, sensu stricto) spikelets occur throughout the range of the species and seem quite distinct, but their status needs further investigation.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 85. L. supinum} (Girard) Pignatti,{\i  Collect. Bot.} ({\i Barcelona}){\b  6:} 309 (1962) ({\i Statice salsuginosa} Boiss.). Plant glabrous, slightly rough. Leaves 35-50 × 11-14 mm, oblanceolate-spathulate, 3-veined, usually withered at anthesis. Inflorescence 20-30 cm hemispherical, much-branched; lower branches mostly non-flowering; scales 4-6 mm. Spikes 1-1·5 cm, with 6 spikelets per cm; spikelets 1(-2)-flowered. Bracts with narrow hyaline margin; inner bract c. 2 mm; outer bract c. 0·5 mm. Calyx c. 3 mm. Corolla c. 4 mm. 2n = 26-27.{\i  Gypsaceous soils, usually inland. • S.E. Spain} ({\i Almeria to Alicante}). Hs.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Coastal populations are sometimes intermediate between{\b  56} and {\b 85}, and have well-developed leaves at anthesis, large spikes and more incurved spikelets. Plants intermediate between {\b 77} and {\b 85} are very common. A rather distinct variant (var. {\i diegoi} (Sennen) Pignatti, {\i L. diegoi} Sennen) has 7- to 9-veined leaves and a larger inflorescence (up to 60 cm) and is perhaps a hybrid between {\b 85} and {\b 77}({\b b}).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 86. L. suffruticosum} (L.) O. Kuntze,{\i  Rev. Gen. Pl.}{\b  2:} 396 (1891). Dwarf shrub with leafy basal branches 2-5 cm. Leaves 15-25(-70) × 2-5 mm, linear-subspathulate, 1-veined, fleshy, glaucous, enlarged at base into an auriculate sheath. Inflorescence 10-20 cm, distichous, spicate, usually simple or little-branched; non-flowering branches absent. Spikes 0·7-1 cm subglobose, inserted on the main axis, sessile, very dense, spikelets 2- to 3-flowered. Inner bract c. 3 mm. Calyx 3-4·5 mm, conical. Corolla whitish. {\i Saline soils. S.E. part of U.S.S.R.} Rs (W, K, E).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 87. L. echioides} (L.) Miller,{\i  Gard. Dict.} ed. 8, no. 11 (1768) ({\i Statice echioides} L.). Annual 5-30(-40) cm. Leaves 20-40 × 10-14 mm, obovate to spathulate, obscurely pinnately veined, with tuberculate glands. Scales (3-)5-6 mm. Spikes 2-10 (-20) cm, with up to 2 spikelets per cm; spikelets 2-flowered, curved. Inner bract 4-5 mm, tuberculate dorsally; outer bract overlapping 1/6 of the inner. Calyx c. 5 mm; teeth becoming uncinate in fruit. Corolla pinkish, evanescent. 2n = 18. {\i Dry, saline soils. Mediterranean region, S. Portugal}. Bl Co Cr Ga Gr Hs It Lu Sa Si.
\par

